[codex] # CONTEXT 5: How the analysis was actually computed
[codex] 
[codex] The R script `de_meta_by_attribute_type.R` does the following:
[codex] 1. Takes per-study results from `de_4b_concern_results.csv` covering Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, 4B (the five studies where participants generated their own initial portfolios).
[codex] 2. For each attribute (target = gender/race; comparison = three other binary attributes per study), it has: main effect, below-pool subgroup effect, above-pool subgroup effect (each in pp), each with a derived SE from |z| = qnorm(1 - p/2).
[codex] 3. Pools across studies using random-effects REML meta-analysis (`metafor::rma`).
[codex] 4. Computes critical-cell pools and contrasts:
[codex]    - Target effect among At/Above-Pool participants (k=5)
[codex]    - Comparison effect among Below-Pool participants (k=15)
[codex]    - Contrast between the two
[codex] 
[codex] The Below-Pool subgroup is defined PER PARTICIPANT PER ATTRIBUTE: a participant is "Below-Pool" for attribute X in study Y if the proportion of their initial portfolio that has attribute X is strictly below X's pool base rate. Otherwise (equal or above) they are "At/Above-Pool."
